      <title>15.04 A Big Cat</title>
      <link>https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/15-04-a-big-cat/</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/15-04-a-big-cat/</guid>
      <pubDate>Sat, 15 Nov 2025 10:59:27 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;main class="wp-block-group is-layout-flow wp-block-group-is-layout-flow"&gt; &lt;div class="wp-block-group is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained"&gt;&lt;h1 class="wp-block-post-title"&gt;15.04 A Big&amp;nbsp;Cat&lt;/h1&gt;   &lt;div style="height:1px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;   &lt;/div&gt;   &lt;div class="entry-content wp-block-post-content is-layout-constrained wp-block-post-content-is-layout-constrained"&gt; &lt;p&gt;(&lt;a href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/15-03-peach-blossom-bookstore/"&gt;Previous Chapter&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao may have had Xiongmao reserve an identical copy of the book and look into its copyist for her, but that would take time, too. She would like to keep an eye on Chou’u’s situation for a bit longer as well, but a problem just came up.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Go see the Moon Prince,” Court Physician Liu said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Today?” Maomao asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Today.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It was about going to give Jinshi his regular medical check-up.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Although she wasn’t as opposed as she was in the past, she was afraid that Jinshi would see right through her and uncover everything that was troubling her. That being said, she couldn’t refuse an order from Court Physician Liu, so off she went.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Thanks always.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao bowed her head at the guards, then entered the room. They were the usual familiar faces, but she still had yet to learn their names.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Jinshi was swirling a cup with one hand while holding documents with the other. It was so warm in the room that it didn’t feel like winter. There was a long-pile rug laid out and a lap blanket draped over the daybed.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“You’re here,” he said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao raised her head. Jinshi’s workload should have decreased, but it must have become a routine for him to bring work home. The cases didn’t look important either.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I have come to give you a health check,” she said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Got it,” he replied.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao took out a notebook.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What’s that?” he asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“If I don’t make a record, it’ll be negligence. So I thought of adding more questions in addition to the palpation and such we’ve done up until now.” Maomao had thought about various things in her own way.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Pardon me.” She drew over to Jinshi, then pulled down his lower eyelids, and had him stick out his tongue for her. She took his pulse and listened to his heartbeat.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“…”&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao ignored the indescribable gaze on her and did her job. “And now, a question.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;As usual, she would first check to see if he had any physical discomfort or abnormalities. She added the new questions as a supplement. “I would like to know what and how much you eat every day in your meals. The same goes for your drinking, including wine or water.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I don’t remember&lt;em&gt; every single detail&lt;/em&gt;.” Jinshi eyed the ceiling in annoyance, but he was spared from thinking. Suiren sidled over and set down a notebook that recorded his daily meals.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Thank you very much,” Maomao said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I will also write the quantity in full detail from now on,” Suiren said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“A rough amount will not be a problem.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The nanny was too capable. Maomao set the notebook aside, planning to copy it down later.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Next, how many times do you go to the toilet every day?” she asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Toilet…” he trailed off.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Please tell me specifically how many times you defecate.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Defecate…” Jinshi froze.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Okaaay, Maomao-saaan.” Chue suddenly appeared. “You can’t go any further. You caaan’t.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Why can’t I?” Maomao asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Chue chastised Maomao, wagging her finger and shaking her head. “Everyone’s idol does not go to pick flowers.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“&amp;#8230;I just wanted to check his condition. Rather, you’ll die if you don’t release what needs to be released, no?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Aaaanyway, anymore of this topic is forbidden. If he feels anything out of the ordinary, the Moon Prince will tell you himself, or Suiren-sama wiiill.” Chue placed a chair behind Maomao and gestured for her to sit. “How about you two make small talk insteaad?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao didn’t really want to chat while she wasn’t clear about Chou’u and the author of the book in question.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Apparently, it wasn’t the case for Jinshi.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“If there’s anything out of the ordinary, I’ll inform you myself. More importantly…” Jinshi signalled to Suiren with his eyes. “An interesting item appeared on the market, so I got my hands on one.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;What could it be? &lt;/em&gt;Maomao wondered.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Suiren brought over a small teapot. The details on this piece were exquisite. It looked like it would fetch a good price.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Behold.” Jinshi poured tea into a teacup. The tea leaves had a pleasant aroma. Was he using extremely expensive tea leaves?&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;He poured tea into another teacup. No, not tea. He was pouring red fruit juice into the teacup.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao compared the contents of the two teacups. They were each filled with a completely different liquid.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What do you think? Fascinating, right?” Jinshi smiled in amusement. “The inside of the teapot has a dual structure. You can pour out two different kinds of liquid.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Ohh.” Maomao studied the teapot with great interest. “It can be used for poisoning.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“&amp;#8230;I guess so.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“From now on, if you see a similar teapot, take caution.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I will do so.” Jinshi, looking a little depressed, pushed the teapot to the edge of the table.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;I was just trying to make conversation.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao felt bad, but she couldn’t help thinking in the direction of a food taster.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;What is there to talk about?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Come to think of it, how are the children at A’duo-sama’s?” she found herself asking. Chou’u’s matter was probably still on her mind.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“The surviving children?” Jinshi said. “How unexpected.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Zhizi-san has gotten much better, so it just came to mind.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Hm. So the girl I left in your custody is growing up well.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yes, she’s very attached to Rahan’s older brother.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“That gentleman does seem to be the type that children would get very attached to.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;There were times the girl got near feral, but it was probably much preferable to being on the brink of death from malnutrition.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Three years have passed since the incident,” Jinshi said. “The children are growing up well with barely any memories of their past. They’re also very attached to A’duo-dono.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao was also aware. It wasn’t just A’duo—Suirei was also looking after them properly.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;However, the children will not be children forever.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What are the plans for the children in the future?” she asked. “Treating them like Suirei is out of the question, right?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Suirei, at the very least, descended from the late emperor. The monitoring of her will not ease for as long as she lives.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“If there are no issues when they reach adulthood, we intend to let them all live independently. It seems they had been left entirely in the care of their wet nurses—their parents fell into depravity before they were old enough to be aware.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Chou’u was the oldest among the surviving children. He would have had to have more memories of his parents than the other children. If he were to recover his memories, how would he behave?&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Don’t remember. Don’t ever remember.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;If he were to feel animosity, even Maomao wouldn’t be able to protect him.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;While drinking tea, deep in thought, her eyes fell upon Jinshi’s documents. There was a crude drawing among the complicated documents.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What’s this?” she asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Ahh, Imperial Princess Lingli drew this for me. Apparently, it’s me,” Jinshi said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“While I can’t quite say it looks like you, it has character.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Right?” He lifted his chin in pride.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;For a time, the imperial princess was more attached to Maomao than Jinshi, but she might have forgotten about Maomao already. Maomao studied the drawing while feeling a bit bitter.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“She’s six this year, right?” she asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yeah.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao only remembered her as a baby. Children grow up fast—the saying also came to mind.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Ow.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao randomly jabbed Jinshi.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Jinshi leaned back in reflex. “Wh-what was that for?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Nothing, I was just thinking that Jinshi-sama from four years ago would have never behaved like this.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Ahhhh. Stop. Stop talking about it. I don’t want to hear it.” Jinshi covered his ears and shook his head. It seems his past actions disturbed him.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“It was a perquisite for palace ladies at the inner palace back then, wasn’t it? To have the opportunity to be greeted by the beautiful lordship that, by all rights, people would have difficulty seeing, even if it was for work,” Maomao said while recalling the sparkling figure.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Are you harassing me?” he asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“No, no, not at all. I was just amused by how much it contrasts with your current appearance.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Hmph.” Jinshi went to lie down on the daybed, sulking.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“If you are going to sleep, please do so in the bedroom.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Jinshi beckoned at Maomao wordlessly. When she came over, he rolled her up in the blanket nearby.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao got cocooned. “What are you up to?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Jinshi must have heard her muffled voice through the blanket. “I wanted to replenish to the point I don’t feel weird,” he said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“This is such an indirect way.” Maomao wriggled, but she couldn’t break free from the tight wrapping.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“You’re somewhat like a real cat.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“There’s no such cat this big.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Should I keep a tiger?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Who will look after it?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Basen.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Ahh.” Maomao could see it.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“That’s irresponsible, so I’ll give it a miss.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Please do that.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Instead, I’ll have you act as the cat.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Ugh. Woof.” Maomao will never ever meow.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;At the same time, she started to settle into her current position, feeling oddly warm and faintly aware of her heartbeat.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;I’ve got to stay awake.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao lightly pinched her cheek while feeling the thumping.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity" /&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;sup&gt;T/N: No new chapter yet, so this one is still the latest. Hopefully I didn&amp;#8217;t just jinx myself.&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;sup&gt;fyi i&amp;#8217;m not done with silksong yet. progress is at 100% but there&amp;#8217;s still this bug&amp;#8217;s high score I&amp;#8217;m struggling to beat for a memento&amp;#8230;&lt;/sup&gt; &lt;sup&gt;I needed a break so here I am.&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p class="has-text-align-right"&gt;(Next Chapter)&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;div id="jp-post-flair" class="sharedaddy sd-like-enabled"&gt;&lt;div class="sharedaddy sd-sharing-enabled"&gt;&lt;div class="robots-nocontent sd-block sd-social sd-social-official sd-sharing"&gt;&lt;h3 class="sd-title"&gt;Share this:&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="sd-content"&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li class="share-facebook"&gt;&lt;div class="fb-share-button" data-href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/15-04-a-big-cat/" data-layout="button_count"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li class="share-end"&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class='sharedaddy sd-block sd-like jetpack-likes-widget-wrapper jetpack-likes-widget-unloaded' id='like-post-wrapper-130534757-5583-6918b4a0d876c' data-src='//widgets.wp.com/likes/index.html?ver=20251115#blog_id=130534757&amp;amp;post_id=5583&amp;amp;origin=shikarito.wordpress.com&amp;amp;obj_id=130534757-5583-6918b4a0d876c' data-name='like-post-frame-130534757-5583-6918b4a0d876c' data-title='Like or Reblog'&gt;&lt;div class='likes-widget-placeholder post-likes-widget-placeholder' style='height: 55px;'&gt;&lt;span class='button'&gt;&lt;span&gt;Like&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class='loading'&gt;Loading&amp;#8230;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;span class='sd-text-color'&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;a class='sd-link-color' href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/15-04-a-big-cat/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/main&gt;</description>
